Title: Cancer

Overview:
- Cancer is a group of diseases in which abnormal cells grow uncontrollably and may spread to other parts of the body.
- It can affect almost any organ such as the lungs, breast, stomach, skin, or blood.
- Cancer develops over time due to genetic changes in cells.
- Early detection and treatment can significantly improve outcomes.
- Lifestyle, environment, and genetic factors all play a role in cancer risk.

Common Symptoms:
- Unexplained weight loss without dieting or exercise.
- Persistent fatigue or weakness.
- Lump or thickening in any part of the body.
- Changes in skin such as darkening, yellowing, or unusual growths.
- Persistent pain that does not go away.
- Changes in bowel or bladder habits.
- Unusual bleeding or discharge.
- Persistent cough or difficulty swallowing.

Risk Factors:
- Smoking and tobacco use.
- Excessive alcohol consumption.
- Unhealthy diet and lack of physical activity.
- Exposure to harmful chemicals or radiation.
- Family history of cancer.
- Chronic infections or long-term inflammation.
- Obesity and poor lifestyle habits.

Basic Home Diagnosis (Preliminary Checks):
- Observe any unusual or persistent changes in the body.
- Check for lumps, swelling, or abnormal growths.
- Monitor unexplained weight loss or continuous fatigue.
- Note any long-lasting pain or discomfort.
- Track changes in skin, moles, or wounds that do not heal.
- Observe any unusual bleeding or discharge.
- If symptoms persist for weeks, seek medical evaluation immediately.

Management and Prevention:
- Maintain a healthy lifestyle with balanced diet and regular exercise.
- Avoid smoking and limit alcohol consumption.
- Protect yourself from excessive sun exposure.
- Follow regular health screenings as recommended.
- Maintain a healthy body weight.
- Stay physically active.
- Avoid exposure to harmful chemicals and pollutants.
- Follow medical advice and treatment plans if diagnosed.

When to Seek Medical Help:
- Any lump or swelling that does not go away.
- Persistent unexplained pain or fatigue.
- Sudden or unexplained weight loss.
- Changes in skin, moles, or non-healing wounds.
- Continuous cough, bleeding, or digestive problems.
- Symptoms lasting for several weeks without improvement.

